ABSTRACT
The need to store vast amounts of trajectory data becomes
more problematic as GPS-based tracking devices become
increasingly prevalent. There are two commonly used ap-
proaches for compressing trajectory data. The ﬁrst is the
line generalisation approach which aims to ﬁt the trajec-
tory using a series of line segments. The second is to store
the initial data point and then store the remaining data
points as a sequence of successive deltas. This paper illus-
trates that the line generalisation approach is only eﬀective
at reducing data size when given a large error margin. In
contrast, the delta approach only performs lossless compres-
sion. Consequently there is an uncovered gap in which users
expect high compression ratio by giving away only a small
error margin. This paper extends the delta approach by
allowing users to specify a maximum error bound. In addi-
tion, alternative techniques are extensively studied for the
following two key components of any delta-based approach:
predicting the value of the next data point and encoding
leading zeros. We propose new superior techniques for both
of these components and call the resulting system “Trajic”.
Experiments using real trajectory data sets show Trajic can
outperform the state-of-the-art delta compression algorithm
by up to 87% for lossless compression and also signiﬁcantly
outperforms leading line generalisation approaches for error
margins up to approximately 25 metres.
1. INTRODUCTION
The need to store vast amounts of trajectory data becomes
more problematic as GPS-based tracking devices become in-
creasingly prevalent. For example, a ﬂeet of one thousand
cars recording a sample per second requires close to 2 GB
of storage space per day. Databases which archive a back-
log of historical GPS data quickly become encumbered by
such vast amounts of data. To minimise the impact of this
problem, data compression algorithms can be applied to re-
duce storage requirements. Two state-of-the-art approaches

There are a large number of algorithms that take the line
generalisation approach to compressing trajectories [4, 8, 12,
7]. Line generalisation attempts to ﬁt the trajectory points
using a series of line segments with end points selected from
within the original trajectory. These segments are selected
such that the points between the two end points are within a
user-deﬁned maximum error and can therefore be discarded.
The main problem with this approach is that it can only
achieve a high compression ratio when successive data points
are close to being linear. However, real-life trajectories can
contain a lot of curvature, noise and low sampling rates (the
last of which ampliﬁes the eﬀect of curves). The only way
to improve compression in these situations is for the user
to specify a large error margin (such as over 20 metres),
but many users are unwilling to forgo such large amounts of
precision.
Delta compression functions by storing the diﬀerence be-
tween successive data points in a trajectory rather than the
points themselves. Since these deltas are typically small,
they may be encoded to save space. In contrast to line
generalisation, delta compression is still able to achieve rea-
sonable compression ratios despite any noise or curvature.
This is because delta compression only requires successive
points to be close to each other rather than within a line,
and oﬀers a ﬁner granularity of compression than line gen-
eralisation. Since line generalisation either discards or keeps
entire points, if a point is just a little outside the maximum
error bound there is no gain in compression performance.
Delta compression is able to smoothly degrade its compres-
sion ratio if points become further apart.
From the above analysis we can conclude that line general-
isation only signiﬁcantly reduces storage requirements when
maximum error is high and data points are approximately
linear with little noise. In contrast, delta compression is
more consistent and provides lossless compression. Figure
1 illustrates a gap in which users can achieve a good com-
pression ratio with a modest error margin. Although line
generalisation can reach similarly good compression ratios,
it can only do so if precision is sacriﬁced.
In this paper we generalise the delta compression algo-
rithm into a broader class of compression systems which we
will call “residual-based compression”. Such systems have
two core components: a predictor and a method for en-
coding residuals. That is, we recognise that existing delta
compressors eﬀectively predict each point to be the same
as the previous one and store the residual (delta) between
the predicted and actual points. By extensively studying
techniques for predicting points and encoding residuals, as
well as incorporating a lossy element to the system, we are
able to propose a novel residual-based compression algo-
rithm called “Trajic”. This makes Trajic better than exist-
ing delta compression algorithms, even for lossless compres-
sion, and better than line generalisation for a broad range
of error bounds.
Residual-based compression algorithms predict the value
of the next data point and then store small residuals rep-
resenting the diﬀerence between predicted and actual val-
ues. More accurate prediction leads to smaller residuals and
hence better compression ratios. A comparison was made
between ﬁve diﬀerent prediction algorithms ranging from the
simple “constant predictor” (used in existing delta compres-
sion) to an expensive cubic spline predictor. It was found
that a simple, fast predictor, the “temporally-aware linear
predictor”, results in the most accurate predictions. Due to
these results, the Trajic system utilises this predictor.
The residuals which are generated between predicted and
actual points can have a variable number of leading zeros,
and these must be encoded eﬃciently to save on storage
space. We found diﬀerent existing leading zero encoding
schemes to be optimal for diﬀerent residual lengths (the
maximum possible length of a residual minus the number
of leading zeros). Furthermore, we discovered that in real
data sets residual lengths have a skewed distribution. This
led us to develop a novel leading zero encoding scheme that
uses the frequency distribution of residual lengths to dynam-
ically select the most eﬃcient way of storing residuals.
The line generalisation algorithms range in complexity
from O(n log(n)) to O(n
2
). For a large database system it
is desirable to have compression and decompression run in
linear time as these operations must be performed for each
insertion and query. Trajic has linear time complexity.
Experiments using real data sets show that the lossless
compression version of Trajic outperforms the delta com-
pression scheme used in the current state-of-the-art TrajS-
tore system [10] by 33% in terms of compression ratio, whilst
maintaining a similar decompression time. When modest
error bounds of approximately 1 second temporally and 1
metre spatially were allowed, the lossy version of Trajic out-
performs delta compression by 87% in terms of compression
ratio and still maintains a similar decompression time.
This paper makes four main, novel contributions. Firstly,
it identiﬁes the large storage savings that can be gained from
eﬀectively encoding leading zeros of residuals in a residual-
based compression scheme. Secondly, it proposes a fre-
quency distribution based approach to analyze and encode
leading zeros. Thirdly, the encoding scheme is combined
with a complete compression system which accepts a trajec-
tory and user-speciﬁed error bounds as input, outputting a
compressed trajectory. Finally, results are presented which
demonstrate the eﬀectiveness of the algorithm when applied
to real-world data sets. This paper begins by brieﬂy dis-
cussing existing related work and their shortcomings. An
overview of the Trajic system is then detailed. Next, the sys-
tem is explained in depth, starting with the predictor then
continuing with the generation of residuals, leading zero en-
coding and ﬁnally the method by which the residuals are
stored. Experimental results and comparisons to existing
schemes are given, concluding with a summary.
1.1 Related Work
There has been a considerable amount of related work
undertaken in recent years on the compression of trajectory
data.
One of the most commonly utilised schemes is line general-
isation with synchronous Eulidean distance [4, 8, 12, 7]. Al-
though under certain conditions this approach can produce
good compression ratios, the algorithms proposed range in
complexity from O(n log(n)) to O(n
2
). For a large database
system, it is desirable to have compression and decompres-
sion run in linear time; these operations must be performed
for each insertion and query. Furthermore, the line gener-
alisation approach is inherently lossy and cannot produce
acceptable compression ratios when zero error tolerance is
desired.
TrajStore [10], an existing state-of-the-art trajectory database
system, handles the compression of trajectories as part of
its functionality. In order to perform single-trajectory com-
pression in linear time, TrajStore employs simple delta com-
pression which essentially stores the diﬀerence between sam-
ple points rather than the points themselves. Whilst this
achieves the time eﬃciency required in a database system,
the algorithm does not take advantage of key properties of
trajectory data. These properties include the fact that mov-
ing objects tend to have inertia rather than erradicly chang-
ing direction. As a result, delta compression does not cause
particulary large reductions in storage space. To improve
on compression ratios, TrajStore clusters similar trajecto-
ries together. This is a complementary technique that may
also be used in conjunction with the Trajic algorithm.
There are other systems which use knowledge of prede-
ﬁned road networks and tracks to minimise the space re-
quired when storing trajectories [3, 13]. However, such sys-
tems are not very useful when the network data becomes
outdated, or the moving objects are not conﬁned to well-
deﬁned tracks. The Trajic compression scheme does not re-
quire such additional network information to compress tra-
jectories.

2.2 Predicting points
In this section we present a range of predictors, start-
ing with the simple constant predictor and ending with our
temporally-aware linear predictor. To design a good predic-
tor, two important factors must be taken into consideration:
accuracy and eﬃciency. An accurate predictor produces pre-
dicted points which are close to the actual future points,
thus minimizing residual sizes and reducing the ﬁnal storage
space required to store compressed trajectories. An eﬃcient
predictor predicts points quickly. Since the predictor is run
for almost every point in a trajectory, it is not feasible to
make predictions based on all past points as this results in an

ity at O(n), only predictors which run in constant time are
considered. Given that a trajectory consists of a sequence of
points containing time, latitude and longitude, a predictor is
composed of separate functions for predicting the temporal
and spatial elements of each point. This enables the tempo-
ral prediction to be run ﬁrst so that the actual timestamp
of the next point can be passed into the spatial prediction
function, facilitating more accurate predictions of latitude
and longitude.
2.2.1 Constant predictor
The constant predictor is one of the most eﬃcient predic-
tors possible - it simply predicts the next point to be the
same as the current one. That is, predicted point #2 is
placed in the same location as actual point #1, predicted
point #3 is placed at actual point #2 and so forth. This
essentially corresponds to delta compression, as the result is
storing residuals between each pair of adjacent points in the
actual trajectory (the “deltas”).
Such a predictor is very simple to implement, and works
best when samples are taken frequently with small changes
between them. Realistically this is not often the case due
to the costs associated with measuring and storing high-
resolution data on portable GPS devices. Hence constant
predictors can perform poorly on real-life data due to its
courser nature.
2.2.2 Linear predictor
The linear predictor functions by considering the previous
two points and calculating the displacement between them.
It then adds this displacement to the last point, thus form-
ing a prediction. In general this performs better than the
constant predictor because it takes advantage of the ten-
dency of moving objects to have inertia. However, when
points are not recorded at a constant sample rate the sim-
ple displacement-based algorithm presented here begins to
lose some of its accuracy. For example, if the previous two
points were sampled ﬁve seconds apart, but the next point
was sampled only one second afterwards, this predictor will

2.2.3 Temporally-aware linear predictor
The temporally-aware linear predictor extends the basic
linear predictor described previously by taking advantage of
the fact that the timestamp of the next point is available
when predicting its location. That is, we make predictions
based on velocity rather than displacement, thus eliminating
the loss of spatial accuracy caused by a variable sample rate.
This is equivalent to the predictor used in [5].
Table 1 contains a sample set of trajectory points for an
object moving with constant velocity but recording positions
with a variable sample rate. The basic linear predictor ig-
nores time and assumes that the displacement between the
second and third points will be the same as that between
the ﬁrst and second. This results in a predicted latitude of
20, which is a considerable overestimation of the actual lat-
itude, 12. However, the temporally-aware linear predictor
calculates the velocity between the ﬁrst and second points,
assumes constant velocity and hence accurately predicts the
next latitude to be 12. Although this is a manufactured ex-
ample, it emphasizes the importance of giving time special
consideration when forming predictions. Figure 4 demon-
strates this anticipated improvement in accuracy by illus-
trating that the temporally-aware predictor achieves smaller
residuals as we add more variance to the sample rate by re-
moving points at random.

2.3 Generating residuals
A residual is a typically small number representing the dif-
ference between two similar values. Given either value, the
other may be restored by using the residual. In this case
the two values are the predicted and actual coordinates in
the form of double-precision ﬂoating-point numbers. Resid-
uals are calculated by XORing the binary representation of
these values. This works because the most important parts
of a double, the sign and exponent, are stored in the most
signiﬁcant of the 64 bits (Figure 5). Therefore, since similar
numbers tend to share a sign, exponent, and a few signiﬁ-
cant bits of the mantissa, residuals will tend to have many
leading zeroes. An example residual calculation is demon-
strated in Table 3.

2.3.1 Lossy compression
In this section we introduce lossy compression by using
approximate residuals which, when restored, are within a
known error margin of the original value. This enables the
creation of much smaller residuals through the usage of bit-
shifts, eﬀectively discarding the D least signiﬁcant bits from
each residual. Ultimately, smaller residuals require less stor-
age space and are desirable. It is ideal to use a diﬀerent value
of D for spatial and temporal residuals as the range of values
and error requirements for each are usually diﬀerent.
Here we perform error calculations based on the IEEE 754
standard for storing double-precision ﬂoating-point num-
bers, but the formulae presented should apply to other rep-
resentations of doubles with slight modiﬁcation.

At this stage we have a sequence of triples containing the
residuals for time, latitude and longitude, which is suﬃcient
data to store the trajectory. Consider each set of residu-
als independently (time, latitude and longitude). That is,
apply these steps three times, then interleave the encoded
residuals when they are written. By doing this the indi-
vidual trends of each coordinate’s residuals are exploited to
facilitate maximum compression.
Although each residual is typically a small number, they
are still technically 64-bit longs. To actually achieve com-
pression the leading zeros of the residuals must be compactly
encoded.
In general, a number stored with a leading-zero encoding
scheme has three sections: a header indicating how many
bits are to follow, a small amount of zeros for padding, and
then the actual data representing the number. Let l be the
length of the actual data in bits (l ∈ [0, 64]). Let p(l) be
the length of the actual data including zero padding in bits
(p(l) ≥ l). Let h be the length of the header in bits (the
header indicates the value of p(l)). Each of these values are
shown in Figure 7. The eﬀectiveness of such an encoding
scheme can be evaluated by examining how few bits are
used in excess of the l actual data bits to store numbers.
The number of excess bits for a given l is x(l) = h + p(l) − l,
which is equivalent to the sum of the header size and the
number of padding bits. A perfect encoding scheme would
always have x(l) = 0, implying that h = 0 and p(l) = l. In
reality this is not possible as the decoder must have some

So, to devise a good encoder one must reduce the value of

Consider an encoding scheme formulated to minimize padding.
In this case p(l) = l, with the exception of p(0) = 1. For the
scheme to work, the header must be able to indicate all 64
possible output values of p(l). Hence h = log
2

equates to one of the most basic and common schemes for
encoding leading zeros: store a 6-bit count of the number of
bits to come followed by that many bits of actual data, like
in Figure 8. Whilst this particular method has no padding
and hence p(l) = l, which is one of the requirements for a
perfect encoding scheme, the constantly high value of h = 6
means that the number of excess bits which must be used to
store each number is x(l) = h + p(l) − l = 6 + l − l = 6 (with
a special case of x(0) = 7). Since x(l) represents the stor-
age overhead associated with data of length l, it is desirable
to achieve better results than a constant 6-bit overhead for
each number.
Another scheme uses h = 4 bits to store a count of the
following half-bytes which contain the actual data, minus
one. That is, p(l) = 4 × (header value + 1). This results
in a saw-tooth style pattern of values for x(l), with minimal
excess bits ocurring when l is a multiple of 4 (see Figure 9).
The average value of x(l) is 5.54, an improvement over the
bit-counting method described previously. A similar encod-
ing scheme uses a h = 3 bit header to store a count of the
following bytes, which results in an average x(l) of 6.57.

the majority of numbers have l = 32 then it will actually
perform best for that particular data set. Therefore optimal
compression can only be achieved if analysis is performed on
the complete sequence of residuals and an encoding scheme
is selected based on the distribution of l values.
2.4.1 Dynamic leading zero encoding
The system for encoding leading zeros proposed here dy-
namically generates a function p(l) based on the frequency
distribution of l values in the sequence of residuals. To en-
sure an optimal function is obtained, a variation of the lin-
ear partitioning algorithm [14] is employed. This results in
values of p(l) that are close to l for the most frequent l val-
ues. Finally, Huﬀman coding [2] is applied to minimize the
header length for most frequently used values of p(l).
To ﬁnd p(l), begin by iterating over the residuals and cal-
culating the frequency with which each l value occurs as a
decimal fraction. This process generates a frequency dis-
tribution consisting of 65 fractions corresponding to each
possible l value, and totalling 1 (Figure 10). Furthermore,
Figure 10 demonstrates a distinct clustering of residual sizes,
which is the main feature exploited by this dynamic leading
zero encoding scheme.
In order to select an eﬃcient function p(l) from a given
frequency distribution, determine the optimal way of parti-
tioning the frequencies using a varying number of dividers.
Within this scheme p(l) is simply a function which rounds l
up to the next divider. Since the algorithm aims to minimise
the average number of excess bits used to store residuals, the
total cost of a particular partitioning must approximate the
average number of excess bits.

By ﬁnding the number and arrangement of dividers with
lowest total cost, we ﬁnd an eﬃcient function p(l) which may
be used to compactly encode the set of residuals. In order
to do this, a variation of the linear partitioning algorithm
[14] is employed (Algorithm 4).
2.4.2 Storing the codewords and data
From the previous section a desirable function p(l) may be
obtained. However, recall that x(l) is calculated using both
p(l) and h. Here a method of minimizing the header length,
h, for the most commonly used values of p(l) is proposed to
complete the dynamic encoding scheme. This is achieved by
using Huﬀman codewords as headers [2]. Huﬀman encoding
works well here because of its ability to reduce codeword
sizes based on how frequently they are used.
A Huﬀman codeword is assigned to each possible divider/out-
put value of p(l), with a divider’s frequency (for the purposes
of Huﬀman coding) being the sum of all frequencies for l val-
ues between it and the next smallest divider. Once the code-
books for time, latitude and longitude are written, residuals
may be stored by writing the appropriate codeword as the
header, followed by p(l) bits containing the actual residual
data.

3. EXPERIMENTS
3.1 Experimental setup
3.1.1 Implementation and hardware
The Trajic system was implemented and tested via C++11
code compiled with GCC version 4.7.2 using the -O3 opti-
mization ﬂag. Results were produced on an AMD Phenom
II X4 965 processor clocked at 3.4 GHz with 4 gigabytes of
RAM, running Ubuntu 12.10, Linux kernel version 3.5.0-21.
3.1.2 Algorithms implemented
Haversine formula The haversine formula [15] was used
to convert degrees of latitude and longitude into kilo-
metres.
Delta compression A simple delta compression algorithm
was implemented with a bit-count leading zero encod-
ing scheme.
Douglas-Peucker The Douglas-Peucker (DP) algorithm is
used in leading line generalisation compression sys-
tems. It was hence utilized in conjunction with delta
compression (described above) to represent the line
generalisation approach in these experiments.
3.1.3 Data sets
The two main data sets used for the experiments are a set
of trajectories recorded by the University of Illinois [9] and
data from the Microsoft GeoLife project [6].
The GeoLife data contains 17,621 trajectories taken with
a variety of GPS devices, and the set includes many modes
of transport including walking, cycling and driving. Over
48,000 hours of data taken from April 2007 to October 2011
is contained in the complete data set.
There are 213 trajectories recorded by the University of
Illinois used in these experiments. This data corresponds to
the movements of two people over a 6 month period.
3.2 Results
Comparisons for Trajic were made to simple delta com-
pression and the Douglas- Peucker line generalisation method,
as described in Section 3.1.2.

3.2.1 Compression ratio
Compression ratio was measured by dividing the total size
of compressed data by the amount of space which would be
required if each sample point were to be stored in 24 bytes
(a 64-bit double for each of time, latitude and longitude).
Reasonably strict error bounds of 1 second temporally and
0.00001 degrees spatially (approximately 1 metre) were used
for the lossy Trajic compression (Table 5).
It is evident that the storage gains from Trajic are sig-
niﬁcant, with as much as 93% of space being saved with
minimal impact on data integrity. Both the lossless and a
lossy version of the Trajic compression system achieve sig-
niﬁcantly better compression ratios than line generalisation
and delta compression for small to medium error bounds.
3.2.2 Running time
In order to test the time performance of the compression
algorithm presented in this paper, the average time taken
to compress/decompress a trajectory was measured (Table
5). Once again, the error bounds for lossy compression
were set to 1 second temporally and 0.00001 degrees spa-
tially. For both Trajic and DP it was found that allowing
for greater maximum error resulted in a faster decompres-
sion time. This was expected as when either system stores
less data in compressed form it takes less time to restore the
trajectory.
3.2.3 Overall performance
By graphing the results (Figure 12) we can consider both
decompression time and compression ratio simultaneously
to gain an overall impression of performance. The better an
algorithm is, the closer it will be to the origin on the graph.
Performing this kind of analysis analysis it becomes obvi-
ous that Trajic compression is fast as well as eﬀective, and

should not have a detrimental impact on the speed perfor-
mance of a larger database system. The line generalisation
system can only match Trajic’s performance if large error
bounds are permitted (31 metres as opposed to 1 metre).
Furthermore, multiple scatter plots were constructed to
compare compression/decompression time with trajectory
length. These conﬁrmed the time complexity analysis, re-
vealing a linear time complexity for Trajic.
3.2.4 Error bounds
The relationship between speciﬁed error bounds and com-
pression ratio was tested by keeping the temporal error whilst
the varying the spatial error. The resulting graph of com-
pression ratio against maximum error (Figure 13) demon-
strates an interesting property: compression ratio ∝ log(error
bound) for small error bounds in the Trajic system. This
is because the number of discarded bits (referred to as D
earlier) is proportional to the logarithm of the error bound.
While the number of discarded bits is less than most of the
residual lengths (l values), discarding an extra bit eﬀectively
means removing one bit from the storage space required for
each of the majority of residuals. Therefore compression
ratio is proportional to the logarithm of the user-speciﬁed
error bound until the number of discarded bits exceeds the
bulk of residual lengths, as at this stage most residuals are
zero and discarding further bits will not reduce their storage
requirements.
In contrast, the line generalisation algorithm degrades
very quickly as maximum error is reduced, with Trajic be-
coming the superior system for errors less than approxi-
mately 25 metres. At less than 0.2 metres it becomes im-
possible for line generalisation to improve the compression
ratio any further.
4. CONCLUSION
4.1 Integration with other systems
The compressor proposed here is independent in that it
can compress and decompress trajectories without any ad-
ditional requirements, such as knowledge of a road map or
historical data. Consequently it is not diﬃcult to integrate
the Trajic system into a full trajectory database ensemble.
For example, the delta compression step described in Traj-
Store [10] can be replaced with the method proposed here,
whilst still maintaining the functionality of the rest of the

system as described in the paper; including the clusterer for

4.2 Summary
Trajic is an eﬀective, eﬃcient and ﬂexible compression sys-
tem for the reduction of storage space required for trajectory
data. Both the compressor and decompressor run in linear
time, making the system feasible for database applications.
In addition, the compressor works for any reasonable user-
speciﬁed error bound, achieving good ratios for both lossless
and varying levels of lossy compression. Trajic achieves bet-
ter compression ratios than simple delta compression, does
not require road maps or other network information and
runs at an acceptable speed.
The source code for a working implementation of Tra-
jic may be found at https://github.com/dismaldenizen/
trajic.
